 it with plausible hydrothermal feedstock generation and environmental interconnections. Strengths: (1) The core 10-step pathway (P1/P2) is directly supported by published experimental evidence with detailed mechanistic understanding. (2) The network topology is well-constructed with 4 meaningful hub molecules (HCN, NH3, 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine, 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine) providing proper convergence. (3) The three cyclization variants (rxn_008, rxn_009, and the implicit dry variant) create genuine branching that generates 10 distinct pathways. (4) Environmental flow from Hydrothermal (CO2/N2 reduction) \u2192 Surface (UV and cyanosulfidic chemistry) \u2192 Biochemical (hydrolysis) is well-motivated. (5) Literature alignment is outstanding \u2014 all surface reactions are directly cited from Patel et al. Weaknesses: (1) rxn_015 is labeled Biochemical, but the literature places this nitrile hydrolysis step under Surface cyanosulfidic conditions \u2014 this is a minor labeling issue. (2) rxn_003 (N2 fixation on iron minerals) is the most speculative reaction, with limited experimental support at the required scale. (3) rxn_002 (HCN from CO+NH3 on pyrite) needs stronger citation support. (4) Surface reactions generally lack explicit mineral agent specifications beyond the Cu/H2S system \u2014 the evaluation criteria ask for mineral agents in Surface reactions. (5) The network does not address the chirality problem (L vs D arginine). Overall, this is a high-quality, literature-grounded network that merits approval.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.90,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.9, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008": 0.85, "rxn_010": 0.85, "rxn_011": 0.9, "rxn_012": 0.85, "rxn_013": 0.8, "rxn_014": 0.85, "rxn_015": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.9, "pathway_coherence": 0.93, "environmental_progression": 0.72, "target_ach