othermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-propenenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N4/c5-2-1-3-8-4(6)7/h1,3H2,(H4,6,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9N3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9N3O/c5-4-6-2-1-3(8)7-4/h3,8H,1-2H2,(H3,5,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N4O/c6-3-4(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h4,10H,1-2H2,(H4,7,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N4OS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-(diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydroxy-thioamide intermediate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N4OS/c6-4(11)3(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h3,10H,1-2H2,(H2,6,11)(H4,7,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N4S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-(diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dehydroxylated thioamide intermediate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N4S/c6-4(10)2-1-3-9-5(7)8/h1-3H2,(H2,6,10)(H4,7,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H12N4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-(4-cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanohydrin-guanidine (C6)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H12N4O/c7-4-5(11)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h5,11H,1-3H2,(H4,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H13N5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-(4-amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-aminonitrile arginine precursor\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H13N5/c7-4-5(8)2-1-3-11-6(9)10/h5H,1-3,8H2,(H4,9,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H14N4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-Arginine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to CO (reverse water-gas shift on greigite)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, H2-rich serpentinization fluid, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe3S4) surface, which serves as an analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, and the resulting hydrogen atoms reduce CO2 to CO via a reverse water-gas shift mechanism. Greigite provides the catalytic iron-sulfur surface for electron transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to CO on iron-sulfur minerals is a foundational step in hydrothermal carbon fixation. Roldan et al. (2015, Chemical Communications) demonstrated CO2 activation on greigite surfaces. Yamaguchi et al. (2014, PNAS) showed CO2 reduction to formate/CO under simulated hydrothermal conditions with Fe-Ni sulfide catalysts. This reaction provides the CO feedstock for downstream HCN synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN synthesis from CO and NH3 on iron sulfide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2) and mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker vent conditions, iron sulfide mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and NH3 co-adsorb on the iron sulfide mineral surface. The CO undergoes nucleophilic attack by NH3, forming a formamide-like surface intermediate which is subsequently dehydrated to HCN. The pyrite surface facilitates the dehydration step through Lewis acid catalysis by exposed Fe sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Schrader et al. (2016, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta) demonstrated formation of cyanide species from reduced nitrogen and carbon sources in iron-sulfide-rich hydrothermal systems. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, Science) showed that iron and nickel sulfides catalyze carbon-nitrogen bond formation under hydrothermal conditions. Schulte & Shock (1995, Origins of Life) provided thermodynamic arguments for HCN stability in hydrothermal systems. This reaction provides the primary C1-N building block for the cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal N2 fixation to NH3 on iron minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-600K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4) and native iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing hydrothermal conditions, serpentinization-derived H2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"N2 is reduced to NH3 by H2 on the surface of magnetite and native iron under high temperature and pressure. Iron provides the catalytic surface that weakens the N\u2261N triple bond through multi-center adsorption, analogous to the Haber-Bosch process but at lower temperatures enabled by mineral surface effects and high H2 fugacity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Brandes et al. (1998, Nature, vol. 395, pp. 365-367) demonstrated reduction of N2 to NH3 by FeO at 1000\u00b0C and by magnetite at lower temperatures under hydrothermal pressures. Smirnov et al. (2008, Geochemistry International) showed NH3 formation from N2+H2 on native iron at 300-500\u00b0C. Schoonen & Xu (2001, Astrobiology) reviewed mineral-catalyzed nitrogen fixation in prebiotic settings. This is the primary hydrothermal route to ammonia needed as a nitrogen source for the cyanosulfidic pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Methane dehydrogenation to acetylene on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-600K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"High-temperature hydrothermal or subseafloor conditions, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry in reverse\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methane undergoes catalytic dehydrogenation on magnetite surfaces at elevated temperatures. The iron oxide surface abstracts hydrogen atoms sequentially, producing ethyne (acetylene) via coupling of C1 radicals. This is a reverse Fischer-Tropsch process where light hydrocarbons are converted to unsaturated species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fegley et al. (1986, Nature) demonstrated acetylene production from methane under conditions simulating volcanic lightning and impact-driven shock synthesis. McCollom & Seewald (2007, Chemical Reviews) reviewed Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite surfaces in hydrothermal systems, noting that both forward (CO\u2192hydrocarbons) and reverse processes occur. Acetylene is also produced by volcanic/impact shock processes (Chyba & Sagan, 1992, Nature). This reaction provides one route to the C2 building block acetylene; volcanic outgassing provides an alternative source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical HCN and NH3 production from N2 and CH4\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 240 nm), anoxic early Earth atmosphere, no ozone shield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis of CH4 generates methyl and methylidyne radicals (CH3\u00b7, CH\u00b7); UV photolysis of N2 generates nitrogen atoms. Radical recombination forms HCN (from CH\u00b7 + N\u00b7) and NH3 (from N\u00b7 + 3H\u00b7). TiO2 mineral surfaces act as photocatalysts, generating electron-hole pairs that facilitate radical formation and recombination at the mineral-atmosphere interface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Tian et al. (2011, Earth and Planetary Science Letters) modeled photochemical HCN production rates from early Earth N2/CH4 atmospheres, finding significant HCN flux under UV irradiation. Zahnle (1986, Journal of Geophysical Research) calculated photolysis rates for CH4 and N2 in anoxic atmospheres. Trainer et al. (2006, PNAS) demonstrated HCN formation from N2/CH4 mixtures under UV irradiation in laboratory experiments. TiO2 photocatalysis of atmospheric gases has been demonstrated by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry). This provides an alternative, purely surface-based route to HCN and NH3 independent of hydrothermal sources.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of HCN to cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst and sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), dilute HCN solution, evaporitic pool margins\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes UV-driven dimerization and rearrangement to form cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). UV photolysis of HCN solutions generates CN\u00b7 radicals and hydrogen atoms; recombination and isomerization yields cyanamide. TiO2 surfaces enhance radical generation, and sulfide minerals (stibnite) provide surfaces for concentration and selective transformation of HCN oligomers to cyanamide over other oligomerization products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) note that cyanamide is a prebiotically available feedstock produced by UV irradiation of HCN solutions. Ferris & Orgel (1966, Journal of the American Chemical Society) demonstrated cyanamide formation from HCN under UV irradiation. Cyanamide has also been detected in interstellar space (Turner et al., 1975, Astrophysical Journal), supporting its prebiotic availability. Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry) established TiO2 as a prebiotically relevant photocatalyst for cyanide chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylene + HCN \u2192 Acrylonitrile (nucleophilic addition)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, geothermal/evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (from HCN dissociation) to acetylene. The cyanide attacks the electrophilic acetylenic carbon, forming the C2-C1 bond. The resulting carbanion is protonated to yield acrylonitrile (vinyl nitrile). Sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite) facilitate the reaction by concentrating HCN and acetylene through adsorption and providing a mildly basic surface environment that promotes cyanide ion formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic arginine synthesis pathway. The reaction of HCN with acetylene to form acrylonitrile is a well-established transformation in organic chemistry. Under cyanosulfidic conditions, sulfide mineral surfaces enhance the reaction selectivity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Acrylonitrile + NH3 \u2192 3-Aminopropanenitrile (Michael addition)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, mildly basic pH, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile. The nucleophilic nitrogen of NH3 attacks the \u03b2-carbon of the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated nitrile in a 1,4-addition. Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate both reactants through interlayer adsorption and provide a mildly basic microenvironment that enhances the nucleophilicity of ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 2 of the cyanosulfidic arginine synthesis pathway. Michael addition of amines to acrylonitrile is a facile reaction that proceeds readily at ambient temperature in aqueous solution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"3-Aminopropanenitrile + Cyanamide \u2192 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine (guanidine formation)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, evaporitic pool, moderate concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of the primary amine of 3-aminopropanenitrile to the electrophilic nitrile carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). The amine nitrogen attacks the C\u2261N triple bond, forming the C-N bond that creates the guanidine (amidine) linkage. This introduces the characteristic N=C(NH2)-NH motif that becomes arginine's guanidinium side chain. Montmorillonite clay concentrates both reactants and provides Lewis acid sites that activate the cyanamide nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 3 of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This reaction is the critical step that introduces the guanidine group unique to arginine among proteinogenic amino acids. The authors note that cyanamide concentration relative to other electrophiles (HCN, formaldehyde) controls the selectivity of this step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Dry intramolecular cyclization to pyrimidine (Variant A)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu) with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, evaporitic pool during desiccation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular cyclization under dry conditions \u2014 the terminal guanidine nitrogen attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine, forming the C-N bond that closes the six-membered pyrimidine ring. Residual moisture hydrolyzes the resulting imine at C4 to give the hemiaminal (4-hydroxy). Elemental copper and H2S provide the redox environment that facilitates the cyclization, with Cu acting as an electron-transfer mediator. The dry conditions of the evaporitic cycle concentrate the substrate and favor intramolecular ring closure over intermolecular side reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 Variant A (dry cyclization) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. Elemental copper and H2S are specified as required reagents. Cu is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper occurs in hydrothermal and volcanic deposits. This variant operates during the dry phase of wet-dry cycling.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine (Variant B)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu) with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet phase of cycle, Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Same intramolecular cyclization as Variant A but with explicit water as co-substrate for nitrile hydrolysis during ring closure. Water attacks the activated nitrile carbon simultaneously with or after the intramolecular N-attack, providing the hydroxyl group at C4. The Cu/H2S system mediates the electron transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 Variant B (hydrolytic cyclization) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This variant operates in the aqueous phase and is stoichiometrically distinct from Variant A in that water explicitly participates as a reactant.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine with NH3 release (Variant C)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu) with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet phase, Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, NH3 released as byproduct\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Same intramolecular cyclization as Variant B but with ammonia released as a byproduct of the nitrile-to-hemiaminal conversion. The nitrile undergoes hydrolytic cyclization and the amide nitrogen is expelled as NH3 during ring closure. This variant recycles nitrogen back to the ammonia pool. Cu and H2S mediate the reductive cyclization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 Variant C (hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release). This variant is significant because it recycles NH3 back into the prebiotic pool, potentially supporting downstream reactions (e.g., amination, rxn_017). The three variants represent different stoichiometries of the same fundamental cyclization process.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Ring-opening of pyrimidine by HCN (chain extension)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, HCN-rich pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ring-opening by HCN \u2014 cyanide ion attacks the hemiaminal carbon (C4) of the pyrimidine ring, breaking the C-N bond and opening the ring to give a linear \u03b1-cyanohydrin bearing the guanidine side chain. This regioselective ring-opening/cyanation extends the carbon chain by one unit while introducing a new nitrile handle for subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations. Sulfide mineral surfaces favor the regioselective C4 attack.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 5 of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. HCN opens the pyrimidine ring regioselectively at C4. The authors note that factors controlling this selectivity (pH, HCN concentration, temperature) are important for pathway efficiency. This step is critical for chain extension from C4 to C5.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile thiolysis by H2S (thioamide formation)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\", \"molybdenite (MoS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, H2S-rich environment, geothermal or volcanic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2S adds across the C\u2261N triple bond of the terminal nitrile group, converting it to a thioamide (C(=S)NH2). This is the hallmark cyanosulfidic transformation \u2014 hydrogen sulfide acts as a nucleophile on the nitrile carbon, analogous to hydrolysis but yielding a thioamide instead of an amide. The sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite) provide surfaces that concentrate H2S and substrate, and may activate the nitrile through Lewis acid interactions with exposed metal sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 6 (Reaction T1) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. Nitrile thiolysis by H2S is the signature reaction of cyanosulfidic chemistry. The reaction proceeds under mild conditions in the presence of sulfide minerals, which are abundant in volcanically active surface environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated reductive dehydroxylation (deoxygenation)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu) with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, reductive conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated reductive elimination of the hydroxyl group as water. The thioamide group stabilizes the developing carbocation or radical intermediate at the adjacent carbon. Elemental copper acts as an electron-transfer agent, donating electrons to facilitate the C-O bond cleavage, while H2S provides additional reducing equivalents. The net result is deoxygenation of the carbon skeleton, converting a branched (hydroxyl-bearing) to a linear chain.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 7 (Reaction T2) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. The Cu/H2S reductive dehydroxylation is a distinctive feature of cyanosulfidic chemistry that enables the removal of oxygen functionality introduced during ring-opening.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with hydroxylation (cyanosulfidic cycling)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu) with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, HCN-containing pool, complex exchange reaction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex exchange reaction \u2014 the thioamide (C(=S)NH2) is hydrolyzed/displaced with release of H2S and NH3, while HCN provides a new nitrile group at the terminal carbon. Water participates in the hydroxylation of the carbon adjacent to the new nitrile. This effectively cycles between thioamide and nitrile functional groups, extending the oxidation state cycling characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Cu mediates the electron transfer. The net result is conversion of the C5 thioamide to a C6 cyanohydrin-guanidine with the complete arginine carbon skeleton.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 8 (Reaction T3) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This reaction is the most mechanistically complex step, involving simultaneous thioamide cleavage, HCN incorporation, and hydroxylation. It exemplifies the nitrile \u21cc thioamide cycling that is the hallmark of cyanosulfidic protometabolism. The released H2S and NH3 are recycled into the pool for use in other reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of cyanohydrin (OH \u2192 NH2 substitution)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH3-rich cyanosulfidic pool, concentration by evaporation or clay adsorption\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic substitution \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at C4, converting the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) to the \u03b1-aminonitrile. The reaction proceeds via an SN1 or SN2 mechanism with the hydroxyl as leaving group (possibly activated by protonation under mildly acidic conditions). Montmorillonite clay concentrates both the cyanohydrin substrate and ammonia through interlayer adsorption, increasing the effective concentration and driving the equilibrium toward the aminonitrile product. The C-N bond is thermodynamically more stable than C-O in this context.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 9 (Reaction F1) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This amination introduces the \u03b1-amino group that will be present in the final amino acid product. The ammonia source may be the original hydrothermal/photochemical pool or recycled NH3 from Reactions rxn_012 (Variant C cyclization) and rxn_016 (thioamide-to-nitrile conversion).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid (Strecker-type completion)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Prolonged aqueous conditions, wet phase of evaporitic cycle, mildly acidic to neutral pH. Racemic product formed; enantioselective enrichment possible on chiral mineral surfaces (e.g., quartz, calcite) via differential adsorption (Hazen et al., 2001)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon of the \u03b1-aminonitrile, first forming an amide intermediate (\u03b1-aminoamide), which undergoes further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (\u03b1-amino acid) with release of ammonia. This is the same Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis that produces other amino acids from their aminonitrile precursors. Montmorillonite surfaces catalyze the hydrolysis by concentrating the substrate and providing Lewis acid sites (Al3+, Mg2+) that activate the nitrile. Phosphate minerals (apatite) provide a mildly acidic buffer that promotes hydrolysis. The product is racemic arginine; L-enrichment could occur via enantioselective adsorption on chiral crystal faces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 10 (Reaction F2) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. The authors state this is the same Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis seen in the synthesis of alanine, serine, and glycine under cyanosulfidic conditions. This final hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the amino acid. Note: the product is racemic; the origin of homochirality remains an open question (Hazen, Filley & Goodfriend, 2001, PNAS, demonstrated enantioselective adsorption of amino acids on calcite crystal faces).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal feedstock + dry cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from CO2, N2, CH4 via hydrothermal feedstock generation (CO2\u2192CO\u2192HCN, N2\u2192NH3, CH4\u2192C2H2), surface cyanamide photosynthesis, cyanosulfidic synthesis with dry cyclization (Variant A), and Strecker-type completion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal feedstock + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P1 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B) with explicit water co-substrate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal feedstock + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P1 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant C) that releases NH3 as byproduct, recycling nitrogen. NH3 from rxn_012 can feed into rxn_017 (amination).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + dry cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN and NH3 from surface photochemistry (N2+CH4+UV on TiO2), acetylene from hydrothermal CH4 dehydrogenation, cyanosulfidic synthesis with dry cyclization (Variant A).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P4 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P4 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant C) with NH3 recycling.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + dry cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Mixed sourcing: HCN from hydrothermal CO\u2192HCN route, NH3 from photochemical N2/CH4, acetylene from volcanic outgassing (direct starting material, no rxn_004), dry cyclization (Variant A).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P7 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C)\",\n      \"description\": \"Same as P7 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant C) with NH3 recycling. This pathway features maximal nitrogen recycling: NH3 is produced photochemically, recycled from Variant C cyclization, from thioamide-to-nitrile conversion (rxn_016), and from final hydrolysis (rxn_018).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Fully photochemical feedstock + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)\",\n      \"description\": \"All feedstock from surface photochemistry and volcanic delivery: HCN and NH3 from UV photolysis of N2/CH4 (rxn_005), cyanamide from HCN photolysis (rxn_006), acetylene from volcanic outgassing (direct). No hydrothermal reactions required. This is the most self-contained surface pathway, relying entirely on atmospheric photochemistry and volcanic inputs for the cyanosulfidic synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide \u2014 primary C1 building block used in 5 reactions. Produced by 2 independent routes (hydrothermal and photochemical), consumed in acrylonitrile synthesis, cyanamide synthesis, pyrimidine ring-opening, and thioamide-to-nitrile conversion.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia \u2014 nitrogen source recycled throughout the network. Produced by hydrothermal N2 fixation, photochemical synthesis, and recycled from Variant C cyclization (rxn_012), thioamide-to-nitrile conversion (rxn_016), and nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_018). Consumed in Michael addition (rxn_008) and amination (rxn_017).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine \u2014 the key branch-point intermediate where the guanidine side chain has been established. Produced by guanidine formation (rxn_009) and consumed by three variant cyclization reactions (rxn_010, rxn_011, rxn_012), making it a divergence point that generates 3 pathway branches.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine \u2014 cyclic intermediate that is the convergence point of all three cyclization variants. Produced by dry cyclization (rxn_010), hydrolytic cyclization (rxn_011), or hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release (rxn_012). Consumed by ring-opening with HCN (rxn_013).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"description\": \"2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine \u2014 the C6 cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate with the complete arginine carbon skeleton. Produced by the thioamide-to-nitrile cycling reaction (rxn_016) and consumed by amination (rxn_017). This is the last hub before the final amino acid assembly steps.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Arginine", "overall_strategy": "The network reconstructs the complete cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway to L-arginine demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry), embedded within a broader geochemical network of hydrothermal feedstock generation and surface photochemistry. The core 10-step surface pathway proceeds from acetylene, HCN, ammonia, cyanamide, and H2S through nitrile intermediates, guanidine formation, pyrimidine cyclization (3 variants), thioamide chemistry, and final nitrile hydrolysis. Upstream, hydrothermal CO2 reduction on greigite/magnetite generates CO and HCN; N2 fixation on magnetite/Fe0 produces NH3; methane dehydrogenation yields acetylene. An alternative photochemical route generates HCN and NH3 from N2/CH4 via UV on TiO2. Cyanamide is produced by UV photolysis of HCN. The combination of 2 HCN sources, 2 NH3 sources, and 3 cyclization variants generates 10 distinct pathways converging on L-arginine. Five hub molecules (HCN, NH3, 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine, 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine, 2-(4-cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine) serve as convergence/divergence nodes. All surface reactions specify mineral agents (elemental Cu, stibnite, montmorillonite, TiO2) in addition to the Cu/H2S redox system central to cyanosulfidic chemistry. The racemic product reflects prebiotic conditions; enantioselective enrichment on chiral mineral surfaces (e.g., quartz, calcite) is noted as a plausible downstream process.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "2-propenenitrile", "common_name": "acrylonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "3-aminopropanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H8N4", "iupac_name": "2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine", "common_name": "2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N4/c5-2-1-3-8-4(6)7/h1,3H2,(H4,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H9N3O", "iupac_name": "4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine", "common_name": "4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9N3O/c5-4-6-2-1-3(8)7-4/h3,8H,1-2H2,(H3,5,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H10N4O", "iupac_name": "amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium", "common_name": "cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N4O/c6-3-4(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h4,10H,1-2H2,(H4,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H12N4OS", "iupac_name": "4-(diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide", "common_name": "hydroxy-thioamide intermediate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N4OS/c6-4(11)3(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h3,10H,1-2H2,(H2,6,11)(H4,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H12N4S", "iupac_name": "4-(diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide", "common_name": "dehydroxylated thioamide intermediate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N4S/c6-4(10)2-1-3-9-5(7)8/h1-3H2,(H2,6,10)(H4,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C6H12N4O", "iupac_name": "2-(4-cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine", "common_name": "cyanohydrin-guanidine (C6)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H12N4O/c7-4-5(11)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h5,11H,1-3H2,(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C6H13N5", "iupac_name": "2-(4-amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine", "common_name": "alpha-aminonitrile arginine precursor", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N5/c7-4-5(8)2-1-3-11-6(9)10/h5H,1-3,8H2,(H4,9,10,11)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "L-Arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to CO (reverse water-gas shift on greigite)", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, H2-rich serpentinization fluid, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe3S4) surface, which serves as an analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, and the resulting hydrogen atoms reduce CO2 to CO via a reverse water-gas shift mechanism. Greigite provides the catalytic iron-sulfur surface for electron transfer.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to CO on iron-sulfur minerals is a foundational step in hydrothermal carbon fixation. Roldan et al. (2015, Chemical Communications) demonstrated CO2 activation on greigite surfaces. Yamaguchi et al. (2014, PNAS) showed CO2 reduction to formate/CO under simulated hydrothermal conditions with Fe-Ni sulfide catalysts. This reaction provides the CO feedstock for downstream HCN synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "HCN synthesis from CO and NH3 on iron sulfide", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2) and mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Black smoker vent conditions, iron sulfide mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "CO and NH3 co-adsorb on the iron sulfide mineral surface. The CO undergoes nucleophilic attack by NH3, forming a formamide-like surface intermediate which is subsequently dehydrated to HCN. The pyrite surface facilitates the dehydration step through Lewis acid catalysis by exposed Fe sites.", "reasoning": "Schrader et al. (2016, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta) demonstrated formation of cyanide species from reduced nitrogen and carbon sources in iron-sulfide-rich hydrothermal systems. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, Science) showed that iron and nickel sulfides catalyze carbon-nitrogen bond formation under hydrothermal conditions. Schulte & Shock (1995, Origins of Life) provided thermodynamic arguments for HCN stability in hydrothermal systems. This reaction provides the primary C1-N building block for the cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal N2 fixation to NH3 on iron minerals", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-600K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4) and native iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing hydrothermal conditions, serpentinization-derived H2"}, "mechanism": "N2 is reduced to NH3 by H2 on the surface of magnetite and native iron under high temperature and pressure. Iron provides the catalytic surface that weakens the N\u2261N triple bond through multi-center adsorption, analogous to the Haber-Bosch process but at lower temperatures enabled by mineral surface effects and high H2 fugacity.", "reasoning": "Brandes et al. (1998, Nature, vol. 395, pp. 365-367) demonstrated reduction of N2 to NH3 by FeO at 1000\u00b0C and by magnetite at lower temperatures under hydrothermal pressures. Smirnov et al. (2008, Geochemistry International) showed NH3 formation from N2+H2 on native iron at 300-500\u00b0C. Schoonen & Xu (2001, Astrobiology) reviewed mineral-catalyzed nitrogen fixation in prebiotic settings. This is the primary hydrothermal route to ammonia needed as a nitrogen source for the cyanosulfidic pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Methane dehydrogenation to acetylene on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-600K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": false, "other": "High-temperature hydrothermal or subseafloor conditions, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry in reverse"}, "mechanism": "Methane undergoes catalytic dehydrogenation on magnetite surfaces at elevated temperatures. The iron oxide surface abstracts hydrogen atoms sequentially, producing ethyne (acetylene) via coupling of C1 radicals. This is a reverse Fischer-Tropsch process where light hydrocarbons are converted to unsaturated species.", "reasoning": "Fegley et al. (1986, Nature) demonstrated acetylene production from methane under conditions simulating volcanic lightning and impact-driven shock synthesis. McCollom & Seewald (2007, Chemical Reviews) reviewed Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite surfaces in hydrothermal systems, noting that both forward (CO\u2192hydrocarbons) and reverse processes occur. Acetylene is also produced by volcanic/impact shock processes (Chyba & Sagan, 1992, Nature). This reaction provides one route to the C2 building block acetylene; volcanic outgassing provides an alternative source."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Photochemical HCN and NH3 production from N2 and CH4", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst", "aqueous": false, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 240 nm), anoxic early Earth atmosphere, no ozone shield"}, "mechanism": "UV photolysis of CH4 generates methyl and methylidyne radicals (CH3\u00b7, CH\u00b7); UV photolysis of N2 generates nitrogen atoms. Radical recombination forms HCN (from CH\u00b7 + N\u00b7) and NH3 (from N\u00b7 + 3H\u00b7). TiO2 mineral surfaces act as photocatalysts, generating electron-hole pairs that facilitate radical formation and recombination at the mineral-atmosphere interface.", "reasoning": "Tian et al. (2011, Earth and Planetary Science Letters) modeled photochemical HCN production rates from early Earth N2/CH4 atmospheres, finding significant HCN flux under UV irradiation. Zahnle (1986, Journal of Geophysical Research) calculated photolysis rates for CH4 and N2 in anoxic atmospheres. Trainer et al. (2006, PNAS) demonstrated HCN formation from N2/CH4 mixtures under UV irradiation in laboratory experiments. TiO2 photocatalysis of atmospheric gases has been demonstrated by Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry). This provides an alternative, purely surface-based route to HCN and NH3 independent of hydrothermal sources."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV photolysis of HCN to cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst and sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), dilute HCN solution, evaporitic pool margins"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes UV-driven dimerization and rearrangement to form cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). UV photolysis of HCN solutions generates CN\u00b7 radicals and hydrogen atoms; recombination and isomerization yields cyanamide. TiO2 surfaces enhance radical generation, and sulfide minerals (stibnite) provide surfaces for concentration and selective transformation of HCN oligomers to cyanamide over other oligomerization products.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) note that cyanamide is a prebiotically available feedstock produced by UV irradiation of HCN solutions. Ferris & Orgel (1966, Journal of the American Chemical Society) demonstrated cyanamide formation from HCN under UV irradiation. Cyanamide has also been detected in interstellar space (Turner et al., 1975, Astrophysical Journal), supporting its prebiotic availability. Ritson & Sutherland (2012, Nature Chemistry) established TiO2 as a prebiotically relevant photocatalyst for cyanide chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Acetylene + HCN \u2192 Acrylonitrile (nucleophilic addition)", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb2S3)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, geothermal/evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (from HCN dissociation) to acetylene. The cyanide attacks the electrophilic acetylenic carbon, forming the C2-C1 bond. The resulting carbanion is protonated to yield acrylonitrile (vinyl nitrile). Sulfide mineral surfaces (stibnite) facilitate the reaction by concentrating HCN and acetylene through adsorption and providing a mildly basic surface environment that promotes cyanide ion formation.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic arginine synthesis pathway. The reaction of HCN with acetylene to form acrylonitrile is a well-established transformation in organic chemistry. Under cyanosulfidic conditions, sulfide mineral surfaces enhance the reaction selectivity."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Acrylonitrile + NH3 \u2192 3-Aminopropanenitrile (Michael addition)", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, mildly basic pH, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile. The nucleophilic nitrogen of NH3 attacks the \u03b2-carbon of the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated nitrile in a 1,4-addition. Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate both reactants through interlayer adsorption and provide a mildly basic microenvironment that enhances the nucleophilicity of ammonia.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 2 of the cyanosulfidic arginine synthesis pathway. Michael addition of amines to acrylonitrile is a facile reaction that proceeds readily at ambient temperature in aqueous solution."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "3-Aminopropanenitrile + Cyanamide \u2192 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine (guanidine formation)", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, evaporitic pool, moderate concentration"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of the primary amine of 3-aminopropanenitrile to the electrophilic nitrile carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N). The amine nitrogen attacks the C\u2261N triple bond, forming the C-N bond that creates the guanidine (amidine) linkage. This introduces the characteristic N=C(NH2)-NH motif that becomes arginine's guanidinium side chain. Montmorillonite clay concentrates both reactants and provides Lewis acid sites that activate the cyanamide nitrile.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 3 of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This reaction is the critical step that introduces the guanidine group unique to arginine among proteinogenic amino acids. The authors note that cyanamide concentration relative to other electrophiles (HCN, formaldehyde) controls the selectivity of this step."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Dry intramolecular cyclization to pyrimidine (Variant A)", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu) with H2S", "aqueous": false, "other": "Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, evaporitic pool during desiccation"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular cyclization under dry conditions \u2014 the terminal guanidine nitrogen attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine, forming the C-N bond that closes the six-membered pyrimidine ring. Residual moisture hydrolyzes the resulting imine at C4 to give the hemiaminal (4-hydroxy). Elemental copper and H2S provide the redox environment that facilitates the cyclization, with Cu acting as an electron-transfer mediator. The dry conditions of the evaporitic cycle concentrate the substrate and favor intramolecular ring closure over intermolecular side reactions.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 Variant A (dry cyclization) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. Elemental copper and H2S are specified as required reagents. Cu is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper occurs in hydrothermal and volcanic deposits. This variant operates during the dry phase of wet-dry cycling."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine (Variant B)", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu) with H2S", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wet phase of cycle, Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Same intramolecular cyclization as Variant A but with explicit water as co-substrate for nitrile hydrolysis during ring closure. Water attacks the activated nitrile carbon simultaneously with or after the intramolecular N-attack, providing the hydroxyl group at C4. The Cu/H2S system mediates the electron transfer.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 Variant B (hydrolytic cyclization) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This variant operates in the aqueous phase and is stoichiometrically distinct from Variant A in that water explicitly participates as a reactant."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine with NH3 release (Variant C)", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu) with H2S", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wet phase, Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, NH3 released as byproduct"}, "mechanism": "Same intramolecular cyclization as Variant B but with ammonia released as a byproduct of the nitrile-to-hemiaminal conversion. The nitrile undergoes hydrolytic cyclization and the amide nitrogen is expelled as NH3 during ring closure. This variant recycles nitrogen back to the ammonia pool. Cu and H2S mediate the reductive cyclization.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 Variant C (hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release). This variant is significant because it recycles NH3 back into the prebiotic pool, potentially supporting downstream reactions (e.g., amination, rxn_017). The three variants represent different stoichiometries of the same fundamental cyclization process."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Ring-opening of pyrimidine by HCN (chain extension)", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb2S3)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, HCN-rich pool"}, "mechanism": "Ring-opening by HCN \u2014 cyanide ion attacks the hemiaminal carbon (C4) of the pyrimidine ring, breaking the C-N bond and opening the ring to give a linear \u03b1-cyanohydrin bearing the guanidine side chain. This regioselective ring-opening/cyanation extends the carbon chain by one unit while introducing a new nitrile handle for subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations. Sulfide mineral surfaces favor the regioselective C4 attack.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 5 of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. HCN opens the pyrimidine ring regioselectively at C4. The authors note that factors controlling this selectivity (pH, HCN concentration, temperature) are important for pathway efficiency. This step is critical for chain extension from C4 to C5."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Nitrile thiolysis by H2S (thioamide formation)", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb2S3)", "molybdenite (MoS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, H2S-rich environment, geothermal or volcanic pool"}, "mechanism": "H2S adds across the C\u2261N triple bond of the terminal nitrile group, converting it to a thioamide (C(=S)NH2). This is the hallmark cyanosulfidic transformation \u2014 hydrogen sulfide acts as a nucleophile on the nitrile carbon, analogous to hydrolysis but yielding a thioamide instead of an amide. The sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite) provide surfaces that concentrate H2S and substrate, and may activate the nitrile through Lewis acid interactions with exposed metal sites.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 6 (Reaction T1) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. Nitrile thiolysis by H2S is the signature reaction of cyanosulfidic chemistry. The reaction proceeds under mild conditions in the presence of sulfide minerals, which are abundant in volcanically active surface environments."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Cu/H2S-mediated reductive dehydroxylation (deoxygenation)", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu) with H2S", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, reductive conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu/H2S-mediated reductive elimination of the hydroxyl group as water. The thioamide group stabilizes the developing carbocation or radical intermediate at the adjacent carbon. Elemental copper acts as an electron-transfer agent, donating electrons to facilitate the C-O bond cleavage, while H2S provides additional reducing equivalents. The net result is deoxygenation of the carbon skeleton, converting a branched (hydroxyl-bearing) to a linear chain.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 7 (Reaction T2) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. The Cu/H2S reductive dehydroxylation is a distinctive feature of cyanosulfidic chemistry that enables the removal of oxygen functionality introduced during ring-opening."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with hydroxylation (cyanosulfidic cycling)", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_005", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu) with H2S", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cu/H2S cyanosulfidic redox system, HCN-containing pool, complex exchange reaction"}, "mechanism": "Complex exchange reaction \u2014 the thioamide (C(=S)NH2) is hydrolyzed/displaced with release of H2S and NH3, while HCN provides a new nitrile group at the terminal carbon. Water participates in the hydroxylation of the carbon adjacent to the new nitrile. This effectively cycles between thioamide and nitrile functional groups, extending the oxidation state cycling characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Cu mediates the electron transfer. The net result is conversion of the C5 thioamide to a C6 cyanohydrin-guanidine with the complete arginine carbon skeleton.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 8 (Reaction T3) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This reaction is the most mechanistically complex step, involving simultaneous thioamide cleavage, HCN incorporation, and hydroxylation. It exemplifies the nitrile \u21cc thioamide cycling that is the hallmark of cyanosulfidic protometabolism. The released H2S and NH3 are recycled into the pool for use in other reactions."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Amination of cyanohydrin (OH \u2192 NH2 substitution)", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH3-rich cyanosulfidic pool, concentration by evaporation or clay adsorption"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic substitution \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at C4, converting the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) to the \u03b1-aminonitrile. The reaction proceeds via an SN1 or SN2 mechanism with the hydroxyl as leaving group (possibly activated by protonation under mildly acidic conditions). Montmorillonite clay concentrates both the cyanohydrin substrate and ammonia through interlayer adsorption, increasing the effective concentration and driving the equilibrium toward the aminonitrile product. The C-N bond is thermodynamically more stable than C-O in this context.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 9 (Reaction F1) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. This amination introduces the \u03b1-amino group that will be present in the final amino acid product. The ammonia source may be the original hydrothermal/photochemical pool or recycled NH3 from Reactions rxn_012 (Variant C cyclization) and rxn_016 (thioamide-to-nitrile conversion)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid (Strecker-type completion)", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Prolonged aqueous conditions, wet phase of evaporitic cycle, mildly acidic to neutral pH. Racemic product formed; enantioselective enrichment possible on chiral mineral surfaces (e.g., quartz, calcite) via differential adsorption (Hazen et al., 2001)"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon of the \u03b1-aminonitrile, first forming an amide intermediate (\u03b1-aminoamide), which undergoes further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (\u03b1-amino acid) with release of ammonia. This is the same Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis that produces other amino acids from their aminonitrile precursors. Montmorillonite surfaces catalyze the hydrolysis by concentrating the substrate and providing Lewis acid sites (Al3+, Mg2+) that activate the nitrile. Phosphate minerals (apatite) provide a mildly acidic buffer that promotes hydrolysis. The product is racemic arginine; L-enrichment could occur via enantioselective adsorption on chiral crystal faces.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 10 (Reaction F2) of the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway. The authors state this is the same Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis seen in the synthesis of alanine, serine, and glycine under cyanosulfidic conditions. This final hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the amino acid. Note: the product is racemic; the origin of homochirality remains an open question (Hazen, Filley & Goodfriend, 2001, PNAS, demonstrated enantioselective adsorption of amino acids on calcite crystal faces)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full hydrothermal feedstock + dry cyclization", "description": "Complete pathway from CO2, N2, CH4 via hydrothermal feedstock generation (CO2\u2192CO\u2192HCN, N2\u2192NH3, CH4\u2192C2H2), surface cyanamide photosynthesis, cyanosulfidic synthesis with dry cyclization (Variant A), and Strecker-type completion.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Full hydrothermal feedstock + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)", "description": "Same as P1 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B) with explicit water co-substrate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Full hydrothermal feedstock + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C)", "description": "Same as P1 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant C) that releases NH3 as byproduct, recycling nitrogen. NH3 from rxn_012 can feed into rxn_017 (amination).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + dry cyclization", "description": "HCN and NH3 from surface photochemistry (N2+CH4+UV on TiO2), acetylene from hydrothermal CH4 dehydrogenation, cyanosulfidic synthesis with dry cyclization (Variant A).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)", "description": "Same as P4 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C)", "description": "Same as P4 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant C) with NH3 recycling.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + dry cyclization", "description": "Mixed sourcing: HCN from hydrothermal CO\u2192HCN route, NH3 from photochemical N2/CH4, acetylene from volcanic outgassing (direct starting material, no rxn_004), dry cyclization (Variant A).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)", "description": "Same as P7 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C)", "description": "Same as P7 but using hydrolytic cyclization (Variant C) with NH3 recycling. This pathway features maximal nitrogen recycling: NH3 is produced photochemically, recycled from Variant C cyclization, from thioamide-to-nitrile conversion (rxn_016), and from final hydrolysis (rxn_018).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Fully photochemical feedstock + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B)", "description": "All feedstock from surface photochemistry and volcanic delivery: HCN and NH3 from UV photolysis of N2/CH4 (rxn_005), cyanamide from HCN photolysis (rxn_006), acetylene from volcanic outgassing (direct). No hydrothermal reactions required. This is the most self-contained surface pathway, relying entirely on atmospheric photochemistry and volcanic inputs for the cyanosulfidic synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_019"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Hydrogen cyanide \u2014 primary C1 building block used in 5 reactions. Produced by 2 independent routes (hydrothermal and photochemical), consumed in acrylonitrile synthesis, cyanamide synthesis, pyrimidine ring-opening, and thioamide-to-nitrile conversion.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_016"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Ammonia \u2014 nitrogen source recycled throughout the network. Produced by hydrothermal N2 fixation, photochemical synthesis, and recycled from Variant C cyclization (rxn_012), thioamide-to-nitrile conversion (rxn_016), and nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_018). Consumed in Michael addition (rxn_008) and amination (rxn_017).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_012", "rxn_016", "rxn_018"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine \u2014 the key branch-point intermediate where the guanidine side chain has been established. Produced by guanidine formation (rxn_009) and consumed by three variant cyclization reactions (rxn_010, rxn_011, rxn_012), making it a divergence point that generates 3 pathway branches.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine \u2014 cyclic intermediate that is the convergence point of all three cyclization variants. Produced by dry cyclization (rxn_010), hydrolytic cyclization (rxn_011), or hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release (rxn_012). Consumed by ring-opening with HCN (rxn_013).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_019", "description": "2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine \u2014 the C6 cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate with the complete arginine carbon skeleton. Produced by the thioamide-to-nitrile cycling reaction (rxn_016) and consumed by amination (rxn_017). This is the last hub before the final amino acid assembly steps.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 470367.2151565552, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-14T13:50:31.700959", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Arginine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network reconstructs the complete cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway to L-arginine demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry), embedded within a broader geochemical network of hydrothermal feedstock generation and surface photochemistry. The core 10-step surface pathway proceeds from acetylene, HCN, ammonia, cyanamide, and H2S through nitrile intermediates, guanidine formation, pyrimidine cyclization (3 variants), thioamide chemistry, and final nitrile hydrolysis. Upstream, hydrothermal CO2 reduction on greigite/magnetite generates CO and HCN; N2 fixation on magnetite/Fe0 produces NH3; methane dehydrogenation yields acetylene. An alternative photochemical route generates HCN and NH3 from N2/CH4 via UV on TiO2. Cyanamide is produced by UV photolysis of HCN. The combination of 2 HCN sources, 2 NH3 sources, and 3 cyclization variants generates 10 distinct pathways converging on L-arginine. Five hub molecules (HCN, NH3, 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine, 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine, 2-(4-cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine) serve as convergence/divergence nodes. All surface reactions specify mineral agents (elemental Cu, stibnite, montmorillonite, TiO2) in addition to the Cu/H2S redox system central to cyanosulfidic chemistry. The racemic product reflects prebiotic conditions; enantioselective enrichment on chiral mineral surfaces (e.g., quartz, calcite) is noted as a plausible downstream process.\n\nMOLECULES (21 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: N2 (nitrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_004: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_005: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_006: CH4 (methane) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CO (carbon monoxide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CHN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H2 (acetylene) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: CH2N2 (cyanamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H3N (acrylonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H6N2 (3-aminopropanenitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H8N4 (2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H9N3O (4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C5H10N4O (cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C5H12N4OS (hydroxy-thioamide intermediate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C5H12N4S (dehydroxylated thioamide intermediate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C6H12N4O (cyanohydrin-guanidine (C6)) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_020: C6H13N5 (alpha-aminonitrile arginine precursor) [intermediate]\n  - mol_021: C6H14N4O2 (L-Arginine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (18 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007, mol_004 (CO2 hydrogenation to CO (reverse water-gas shift on greigite)) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_007, mol_009 -> mol_008, mol_004 (HCN synthesis from CO and NH3 on iron sulfide) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_009 (Hydrothermal N2 fixation to NH3 on iron minerals) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006 -> mol_010, mol_002 (Methane dehydrogenation to acetylene on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_003, mol_006 -> mol_008, mol_009 (Photochemical HCN and NH3 production from N2 and CH4) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_008 -> mol_011 (UV photolysis of HCN to cyanamide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_010, mol_008 -> mol_012 (Acetylene + HCN \u2192 Acrylonitrile (nucleophilic addition)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_012, mol_009 -> mol_013 (Acrylonitrile + NH3 \u2192 3-Aminopropanenitrile (Michael addition)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_013, mol_011 -> mol_014 (3-Aminopropanenitrile + Cyanamide \u2192 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine (guanidine formation)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_014 -> mol_015 (Dry intramolecular cyclization to pyrimidine (Variant A)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_014, mol_004 -> mol_015 (Hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine (Variant B)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_014, mol_004 -> mol_015, mol_009 (Hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine with NH3 release (Variant C)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_015, mol_008 -> mol_016 (Ring-opening of pyrimidine by HCN (chain extension)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_016, mol_005 -> mol_017 (Nitrile thiolysis by H2S (thioamide formation)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_017 -> mol_018, mol_004 (Cu/H2S-mediated reductive dehydroxylation (deoxygenation)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_018, mol_004, mol_008 -> mol_019, mol_005, mol_009 (Thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with hydroxylation (cyanosulfidic cycling)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_017: mol_019, mol_009 -> mol_020 (Amination of cyanohydrin (OH \u2192 NH2 substitution)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_018: mol_020, mol_004 -> mol_021, mol_009 (Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid (Strecker-type completion)) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full hydrothermal feedstock + dry cyclization (15 steps)\n  - P2: Full hydrothermal feedstock + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B) (15 steps)\n  - P3: Full hydrothermal feedstock + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C) (15 steps)\n  - P4: Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + dry cyclization (13 steps)\n  - P5: Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B) (13 steps)\n  - P6: Photochemical feedstock + hydrothermal acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C) (13 steps)\n  - P7: Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + dry cyclization (14 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B) (14 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal HCN + photochemical NH3 + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 recycling (Variant C) (14 steps)\n  - P10: Fully photochemical feedstock + volcanic acetylene + hydrolytic cyclization (Variant B) (12 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_008, mol_009, mol_014, mol_015, mol_019\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Arginine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nOne experimentally demonstrated pathway produces L-arginine (C6H14N4O2, SMILES: C(CC(C(=O)O)N)CN=C(N)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10), MW: 174.20) from prebiotically available precursors. The entire pathway operates within the cyanosulfidic (Surface) environment.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-arginine through a 10-step sequence beginning from acetylene, hydrogen cyanide, ammonia, cyanamide, and hydrogen sulfide. The pathway proceeds through nitrile intermediates, guanidine formation, a cyclic pyrimidine intermediate, thioamide chemistry, and final nitrile hydrolysis. Elemental copper and hydrogen sulfide serve as key reagents in several steps (cyclization, dehydroxylation, thioamide-to-nitrile conversion).\n\n**Step 1**: Acetylene + Hydrogen cyanide \u2192 Acrylonitrile\n- SMILES: C#N.C#C>>C=CC#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Addition of HCN across the triple bond of acetylene, forming the vinyl nitrile (acrylonitrile). This is a conjugate addition reaction where the cyanide ion acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic acetylenic carbon.\n\n**Step 2**: Acrylonitrile + Ammonia \u2192 3-Aminopropanenitrile\n- SMILES: C=CC#N.N>>N#CCCN\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile. The nucleophilic nitrogen of NH3 attacks the \u03b2-carbon of the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated nitrile in a 1,4-addition, yielding the \u03b2-amino nitrile (3-aminopropanenitrile).\n\n**Step 3**: 3-Aminopropanenitrile + Cyanamide \u2192 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine\n- SMILES: N#CCCN.N#CN>>N#CCCNC(=N)N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: The primary amine of 3-aminopropanenitrile attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N), forming a guanidine linkage. This nucleophilic addition converts the nitrile of cyanamide into an amidine (guanidine) group, introducing the characteristic N=C(NH2)-NH motif of arginine's side chain.\n\n**Step 4**: 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine \u2192 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine\n- Three variant conditions were reported, all employing elemental copper and hydrogen sulfide as reagents:\n- **Variant A** (dry cyclization): 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine \u2192 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine\n  - SMILES: N#CCCNC(=N)N>>NC1=NCCC(O)N1\n  - Agents: Elemental copper (Cu), hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\n- **Variant B** (hydrolytic cyclization): 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine + H2O \u2192 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine\n  - SMILES: N#CCCNC(=N)N.O>>NC1=NCCC(O)N1\n  - Agents: Elemental copper (Cu), hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\n- **Variant C** (hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release): 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine + H2O \u2192 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine + NH3\n  - SMILES: N#CCCNC(=N)N.O>>NC1=NCCC(O)N1.N\n  - Agents: Elemental copper (Cu), hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Intramolecular cyclization \u2014 the nitrile group of 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine undergoes nucleophilic attack by the terminal guanidine nitrogen, forming a six-membered pyrimidine ring. Water participates in the hydrolysis of the nitrile to a hydroxyl group at the C4 position. Copper and H2S facilitate the reduction/cyclization under cyanosulfidic conditions. The three variants represent different stoichiometries of the same fundamental cyclization process.\n\n**Step 5**: 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine + Hydrogen cyanide \u2192 Amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium\n- SMILES: NC1=NCCC(O)N1.C#N>>N#CC(O)CCNC(=N)N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Ring-opening of the pyrimidine by HCN \u2014 hydrogen cyanide attacks the C4 position of the cyclic hemiaminal, opening the six-membered ring and introducing a cyano group. The hydroxyl group is retained at the carbon bearing the new nitrile, yielding an open-chain \u03b1-cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate.\n\n**Step 6**: Amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium + Hydrogen sulfide \u2192 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCNC(=N)N.S>>N=C(N)NCCC(O)C(N)=S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Thiolysis of the nitrile group \u2014 H2S adds across the C\u2261N triple bond of the cyano group, converting it to a thioamide (C(=S)NH2). This is the characteristic cyanosulfidic transformation where hydrogen sulfide acts as a nucleophile on the nitrile carbon, analogous to hydrolysis but yielding a thioamide instead of an amide.\n\n**Step 7**: 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide \u2192 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide + H2O\n- SMILES: N=C(N)NCCC(O)C(N)=S>>N=C(N)NCCCC(N)=S.O\n- Agents: Elemental copper (Cu), hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Reductive dehydroxylation \u2014 the hydroxyl group adjacent to the thioamide is eliminated as water. Copper and H2S provide the reducing equivalents needed for this deoxygenation step. The carbon skeleton is homologated from a branched (hydroxyl-bearing) to a linear chain.\n\n**Step 8**: 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide + H2O + HCN \u2192 2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine + H2S + NH3\n- SMILES: N=C(N)NCCCC(N)=S.O.[C-]#N>>N#CC(O)CCCNC(=N)N.S.N\n- Agents: Elemental copper (Cu), hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with concomitant hydroxylation \u2014 HCN and water participate in a complex exchange where the thioamide sulfur is displaced (released as H2S), the nitrogen is lost as ammonia, and a new cyanohydrin is formed. This effectively converts the C(=S)NH2 terminus back to a C(OH)(C\u2261N) functionality, extending the oxidation state cycling that is characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**Step 9**: 2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine + Ammonia \u2192 2-(4-Amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCCNC(=N)N.N>>N#CC(N)CCCNC(=N)N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Amination \u2014 the hydroxyl group at C4 is displaced by ammonia in a substitution reaction, replacing -OH with -NH2. This introduces the \u03b1-amino group that will become the amino acid amine in the final product. The cyano group is retained for subsequent hydrolysis.\n\n**Step 10**: 2-(4-Amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Arginine + NH3\n- SMILES: N#CC(N)CCCNC(=N)N.O.O>>N.N=C(N)NCCCC(N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 the terminal nitrile group undergoes stepwise hydrolysis by water, first forming an amide intermediate, then the carboxylic acid, with release of ammonia. This converts the \u03b1-aminonitrile to the \u03b1-amino acid (arginine). This is the same Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis mechanism seen in the synthesis of other amino acids (alanine, serine, glycine) under cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine (C4H8N4)\n- Formula: C4H8N4\n- SMILES: C(CN=C(N)N)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N4/c5-2-1-3-8-4(6)7/h1,3H2,(H4,6,7,8)\n- MW: 112.13\n- Role: **Key branch-point intermediate** \u2014 this is the molecule where the guanidine side chain has been established and that undergoes intramolecular cyclization to the pyrimidine ring. It is the substrate for three variant cyclization reactions (with Cu/H2S), making it a convergence/divergence point in the network.\n\n### Hub Molecule: 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine (C4H9N3O)\n- Formula: C4H9N3O\n- SMILES: C1CN=C(NC1O)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9N3O/c5-4-6-2-1-3(8)7-4/h3,8H,1-2H2,(H3,5,6,7)\n- MW: 115.13\n- Role: **Cyclic intermediate** \u2014 the six-membered pyrimidine ring formed by cyclization of 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine. This ring is subsequently opened by HCN to extend the carbon chain. It is the product of three variant cyclization reactions (convergence point) and the substrate for ring-opening (Step 5).\n\n### Intermediate Molecules\n\n**Acrylonitrile** (C3H3N)\n- Formula: C3H3N\n- SMILES: C=CC#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2\n- MW: 53.06\n- Role: Vinyl nitrile intermediate \u2014 formed from acetylene + HCN, serves as Michael acceptor for ammonia addition.\n\n**3-Aminopropanenitrile** (C3H6N2)\n- Formula: C3H6N2\n- SMILES: C(CN)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,4H2\n- MW: 70.09\n- Role: \u03b2-Amino nitrile intermediate \u2014 formed from acrylonitrile + NH3, reacts with cyanamide to form the guanidine linkage.\n\n**Amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium** (C5H10N4O)\n- Formula: C5H10N4O\n- SMILES: C(CN=C(N)N)C(C#N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H10N4O/c6-3-4(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h4,10H,1-2H2,(H4,7,8,9)\n- MW: 142.16\n- Role: Ring-opened cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate \u2014 formed by HCN opening of the pyrimidine ring. Contains both the nitrile and hydroxyl groups that undergo subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations.\n\n**4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide** (C5H12N4OS)\n- Formula: C5H12N4OS\n- SMILES: C(CN=C(N)N)C(C(=S)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H12N4OS/c6-4(11)3(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h3,10H,1-2H2,(H2,6,11)(H4,7,8,9)\n- MW: 176.24\n- Role: Thioamide intermediate \u2014 formed by H2S thiolysis of the nitrile. The hydroxyl group is subsequently removed by Cu/H2S-mediated dehydroxylation.\n\n**4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide** (C5H12N4S)\n- Formula: C5H12N4S\n- SMILES: C(CC(=S)N)CN=C(N)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H12N4S/c6-4(10)2-1-3-9-5(7)8/h1-3H2,(H2,6,10)(H4,7,8,9)\n- MW: 160.24\n- Role: Dehydroxylated thioamide intermediate \u2014 formed by Cu/H2S-mediated removal of the hydroxyl group. The thioamide is subsequently converted back to a cyanohydrin by HCN exchange.\n\n**2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine** (C6H12N4O)\n- Formula: C6H12N4O\n- SMILES: C(CC(C#N)O)CN=C(N)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C6H12N4O/c7-4-5(11)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h5,11H,1-3H2,(H4,8,9,10)\n- MW: 156.19\n- Role: Cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate \u2014 formed by thioamide-to-nitrile conversion. The hydroxyl group is displaced by ammonia in the next step to form the \u03b1-amino group.\n\n**2-(4-Amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine** (C6H13N5)\n- Formula: C6H13N5\n- SMILES: C(CC(C#N)N)CN=C(N)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C6H13N5/c7-4-5(8)2-1-3-11-6(9)10/h5H,1-3,8H2,(H4,9,10,11)\n- MW: 155.20\n- Role: \u03b1-Aminonitrile precursor \u2014 the direct precursor to arginine. Contains the complete carbon skeleton with \u03b1-amino group and guanidine side chain; only the nitrile-to-carboxylic acid hydrolysis remains.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **Acetylene** (C2H2): SMILES: C#C, InChI: InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H, MW: 26.04\n- **Hydrogen cyanide** (HCN): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03\n- **Ammonia** (NH3): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03\n- **Cyanamide** (CH2N2): SMILES: C(#N)N, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h2H2, MW: 42.04\n- **Hydrogen sulfide** (H2S): SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2, MW: 34.08\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2, MW: 18.02\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Upstream Reactions (Building the Carbon Skeleton and Guanidine)\n\n**Reaction U1: Acetylene + HCN \u2192 Acrylonitrile**\n- Acetylene + Hydrogen cyanide \u2192 Acrylonitrile\n- SMILES: C#N.C#C>>C=CC#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to acetylene, forming the C2-C1 bond. The resulting vinyl nitrile (acrylonitrile) retains both unsaturation and the nitrile electrophilic center for subsequent Michael addition.\n\n**Reaction U2: Acrylonitrile + NH3 \u2192 3-Aminopropanenitrile**\n- Acrylonitrile + Ammonia \u2192 3-Aminopropanenitrile\n- SMILES: C=CC#N.N>>N#CCCN\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Michael addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile. NH3 adds to the \u03b2-carbon of the conjugated system in a 1,4-fashion, yielding the 3-amino nitrile.\n\n**Reaction U3: 3-Aminopropanenitrile + Cyanamide \u2192 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine**\n- 3-Aminopropanenitrile + Cyanamide \u2192 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine\n- SMILES: N#CCCN.N#CN>>N#CCCNC(=N)N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of the primary amine to the nitrile carbon of cyanamide. The amine nitrogen attacks the electrophilic C\u2261N of cyanamide, forming the guanidine (amidine) linkage that becomes arginine's characteristic side-chain functional group.\n\n### Cyclization Reactions (Ring Formation and Opening)\n\n**Reaction C1a: 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine \u2192 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine (dry cyclization)**\n- SMILES: N#CCCNC(=N)N>>NC1=NCCC(O)N1\n- Agents: **Elemental copper** (Cu) and **hydrogen sulfide** (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Intramolecular cyclization \u2014 the terminal guanidine nitrogen attacks the nitrile carbon, forming the C-N bond that closes the six-membered pyrimidine ring. Water from the medium (or intramolecular) hydrolyzes the resulting imine at C4 to give the hemiaminal (hydroxyl at C4).\n\n**Reaction C1b: 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine + H2O \u2192 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine (hydrolytic)**\n- SMILES: N#CCCNC(=N)N.O>>NC1=NCCC(O)N1\n- Agents: **Elemental copper** (Cu) and **hydrogen sulfide** (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Same cyclization as C1a with explicit water as co-substrate for nitrile hydrolysis during ring closure.\n\n**Reaction C1c: 2-(2-Cyanoethyl)guanidine + H2O \u2192 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine + NH3**\n- SMILES: N#CCCNC(=N)N.O>>NC1=NCCC(O)N1.N\n- Agents: **Elemental copper** (Cu) and **hydrogen sulfide** (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Same cyclization as C1b with ammonia released as a byproduct of the nitrile-to-hemiaminal conversion.\n\n**Reaction C2: 4-Hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine + HCN \u2192 Amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium**\n- SMILES: NC1=NCCC(O)N1.C#N>>N#CC(O)CCNC(=N)N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Ring-opening by HCN \u2014 cyanide attacks the hemiaminal carbon (C4) of the pyrimidine ring, breaking the C-N bond and opening the ring. The product is a linear \u03b1-cyanohydrin bearing the guanidine side chain. This ring-opening/cyanation effectively extends the carbon chain by one unit while introducing a new nitrile handle for subsequent transformations.\n\n### Thioamide Chemistry (Cyanosulfidic Transformations)\n\n**Reaction T1: Nitrile thiolysis**\n- Amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium + H2S \u2192 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCNC(=N)N.S>>N=C(N)NCCC(O)C(N)=S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: H2S adds across the nitrile triple bond (C\u2261N \u2192 C(=S)NH2). This is the hallmark cyanosulfidic reaction \u2014 sulfide acts as a nucleophile on the nitrile carbon, converting it to a thioamide. The hydroxyl group at the adjacent carbon is preserved.\n\n**Reaction T2: Reductive dehydroxylation**\n- 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide \u2192 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide + H2O\n- SMILES: N=C(N)NCCC(O)C(N)=S>>N=C(N)NCCCC(N)=S.O\n- Agents: **Elemental copper** (Cu) and **hydrogen sulfide** (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Cu/H2S-mediated reductive elimination of the hydroxyl group as water. The thioamide group facilitates this by stabilizing the developing carbocation or radical intermediate at the adjacent carbon. The net result is deoxygenation of the carbon skeleton.\n\n**Reaction T3: Thioamide-to-nitrile conversion**\n- 4-(Diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide + H2O + HCN \u2192 2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine + H2S + NH3\n- SMILES: N=C(N)NCCCC(N)=S.O.[C-]#N>>N#CC(O)CCCNC(=N)N.S.N\n- Agents: **Elemental copper** (Cu) and **hydrogen sulfide** (H2S)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Complex exchange reaction \u2014 the thioamide is hydrolyzed/displaced, releasing H2S and NH3, while HCN provides a new nitrile group at the terminal carbon. Water participates in the hydrolysis of the thioamide and hydroxylation of the carbon. This reaction effectively cycles between thioamide and nitrile functional groups, a key feature of cyanosulfidic chemistry that enables carbon chain rearrangement.\n\n### Final Steps (Amination and Hydrolysis to Arginine)\n\n**Reaction F1: Amination**\n- 2-(4-Cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine + NH3 \u2192 2-(4-Amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCCNC(=N)N.N>>N#CC(N)CCCNC(=N)N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic substitution \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at C4, converting the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) to the \u03b1-aminonitrile. This introduces the \u03b1-amino group that will be present in the final amino acid product. The reaction is thermodynamically driven by the greater stability of the C-N bond relative to the C-O bond in the aminonitrile context.\n\n**Reaction F2: Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid**\n- 2-(4-Amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Arginine + NH3\n- SMILES: N#CC(N)CCCNC(=N)N.O.O>>N.N=C(N)NCCCC(N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon of the \u03b1-aminonitrile, forming an amide intermediate (\u03b1-aminoamide), which undergoes further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (\u03b1-amino acid) with release of ammonia. This is the same Strecker-type nitrile hydrolysis that produces other amino acids (alanine, serine, glycine) from their respective aminonitrile precursors under aqueous cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe following reagents and catalysts are experimentally documented for reactions in the L-arginine synthesis network:\n\n- **Elemental Copper (Cu)**: Metallic copper serves as a reductant and electron-transfer mediator in the cyanosulfidic reaction network. In combination with hydrogen sulfide, it facilitates: (a) intramolecular cyclization of 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine to the pyrimidine ring (Reactions C1a/b/c), (b) reductive dehydroxylation of the hydroxy-thioamide intermediate (Reaction T2), and (c) thioamide-to-nitrile conversion (Reaction T3). Copper is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper occurs in hydrothermal and volcanic deposits, and copper sulfides are common in sulfide-rich environments. Used in: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202.\n\n- **Hydrogen Sulfide (H2S)**: A key cyanosulfidic reagent that serves dual roles: (a) as a nucleophile that converts nitrile groups to thioamides (Reaction T1), and (b) as a co-reagent with elemental copper in reductive transformations (Reactions C1a/b/c, T2, T3). H2S is abundantly available in volcanic environments, hydrothermal vents, and early Earth surface waters. It is the sulfur source that drives the characteristic nitrile \u21cc thioamide cycling of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Used in: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN, H2S, acetylene, cyanamide, and other simple molecules can produce precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids through an interconnected reaction network. For arginine specifically, the paper establishes a complete 10-step pathway from acetylene and HCN to arginine via a sequence of nitrile additions, guanidine formation (from cyanamide), pyrimidine cyclization (Cu/H2S-mediated), ring-opening by HCN, thioamide chemistry (H2S thiolysis, Cu-mediated dehydroxylation, thioamide-to-nitrile conversion), amination, and final nitrile hydrolysis. The pathway demonstrates how the guanidinium side chain of arginine \u2014 unique among the proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 arises naturally from cyanamide incorporation into a growing nitrile chain. The same cyanosulfidic framework produces precursors to other amino acids (alanine, serine, glycine), nucleotides, and lipid building blocks, supporting a common chemical origin for all major classes of biomolecules.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary \u2014 Cyanosulfidic)\nThe entire arginine synthesis pathway operates under cyanosulfidic surface conditions as described by Patel et al. (2015):\n- **Geochemical setting**: Evaporitic pools or geothermal fields with access to volcanic outgassing products (HCN, H2S, acetylene) and dissolved minerals (copper).\n- **HCN chemistry**: Hydrogen cyanide is the primary C1 building block, used in Steps 1 (with acetylene), 5 (pyrimidine ring-opening), and 8 (thioamide-to-nitrile conversion). HCN is produced by UV photolysis of N2/CH4 atmospheres and by volcanic/impact processes.\n- **Cyanamide**: The nitrogen source for guanidine formation (Step 3). Cyanamide (H2N-C\u2261N) is produced by UV irradiation of HCN solutions and has been detected in interstellar space.\n- **Cu/H2S redox system**: Elemental copper and hydrogen sulfide work in concert to drive reductive cyclization, dehydroxylation, and thioamide cycling. This Cu/H2S system is a distinctive feature of the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n- **Acetylene**: The C2 building block for the initial carbon skeleton (Step 1). Acetylene is produced by UV photolysis of methane, volcanic outgassing, and impact shock synthesis.\n- **Wet-dry cycling**: The aqueous hydrolysis steps (Steps 4, 10) and dehydration steps (Step 7) are consistent with evaporitic pool environments where wet-dry cycles concentrate reactants and drive both hydrolysis and condensation reactions.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\n1. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: H2S and HCN from hydrothermal vents could be transported to surface pools where Cu-mediated cyanosulfidic chemistry occurs.\n2. **Volcanic \u2192 Surface**: Acetylene, HCN, and cyanamide from volcanic/impact sources are deposited into surface water bodies.\n3. **Surface \u2192 Biochemical**: Arginine produced in cyanosulfidic pools enters the prebiotic amino acid inventory, available for peptide bond formation, role as a catalyst/organizer in prebiotic RNA-peptide interactions, and proto-metabolic assembly. Arginine's guanidinium group is particularly important for electrostatic interactions with phosphate groups in nucleic acids.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: The cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic arginine (equal L and D). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved. Possible mechanisms include enantioselective adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces, amplification by autocatalytic crystallization, or circularly polarized light.\n\n2. **Copper availability**: The pathway requires elemental copper for several key steps (cyclization, dehydroxylation, thioamide conversion). The abundance and accessibility of native copper in early Earth surface environments is debated. Copper sulfides are common in sulfide-rich environments but metallic copper requires reducing conditions.\n\n3. **Multi-step yield**: The 10-step linear pathway means that even moderate yields per step compound to low overall yield. For example, 50% yield per step gives ~0.1% overall yield. Concentration mechanisms (evaporation, mineral adsorption, thermophoresis) are needed to accumulate sufficient product.\n\n4. **Cyanamide concentration**: Step 3 requires cyanamide in sufficient concentration to compete with other electrophiles (HCN, formaldehyde) for reaction with 3-aminopropanenitrile. The prebiotic steady-state concentration of cyanamide relative to other cyanide species is uncertain.\n\n5. **Intermediate stability**: Several intermediates contain reactive functional groups (nitriles, thioamides, cyanohydrins) that could undergo side reactions or decomposition under UV irradiation. The selectivity of the pathway depends on kinetic control and the relative rates of productive vs. destructive reactions.\n\n6. **Guanidine uniqueness**: Arginine is the only proteinogenic amino acid with a guanidinium group. The cyanamide-dependent route to this group is specific \u2014 without cyanamide, the pathway cannot produce arginine. This raises questions about whether cyanamide availability was a bottleneck for arginine incorporation into early protein-like polymers.\n\n7. **Ring-opening selectivity**: Step 5 (HCN opening of the pyrimidine ring) must occur regioselectively at C4. The factors controlling this selectivity (pH, HCN concentration, temperature) and the competing ring-opening products have not been fully characterized.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_fee